/i>.","patronymic from either of two Middle English personal names, <i>Cok(k)ing</i> (Old English <i>Coccing</i>) or <i>Cokin</i> (probably Old French in origin), both of which are pet forms of   Cocke   2."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":". Sarah Cockaine was born about 1126, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Andrew Andreas Cokayne of Ashbourne about 1152, in Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1126–":"umbes 1126–Surnud","1122–1189":"1122–1189","1153–1242":"1153–1242","1126–Female":"1126–Surnud","1126":"1126","1189":"1189","1122":"1122","1242":"1242","ABT 1126":"umbes 1126","1153":"1153","about 1152":"umbes 1152","about 1153":"umbes 1153","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","of Ashbowne, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1126–":"noin 1126–Kuollut","1122–1189":"1122–1189","1153–1242":"1153–1242","1126–Female":"1126–Kuollut","1126":"1126","1189":"1189","1122":"1122","1242":"1242","ABT 1126":"noin 1126","1153":"1153","about 1152":"noin 1152","about 1153":"noin 1153","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","of Ashbowne, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhd